data.sampled: This is a classic option pair strategy known as the Strangle. The strategy consists of a buy and a sell option at the same expiration date. The sell option is at a lower strike price and the buy option is at a higher strike price. When the underlying stock price moves higher, both sell and buy options tend to become more expensive than the other, and may lead to further price movement. The strangle strategy can be effective in generating large profit margins, but it requires careful management of the underlying stock price. The premise behind the strangle is that if the market falls within a certain range, the strangle will continue to profit from extreme price movement and retain the option until such time as it is closed out by the market. This can result in substantial trading returns if the market trends continue.
